# Smart Home Framework

This documents overviews the technical implementation details of the Smart Home framework. The goal of this framework is to handle reasoning over sets of aggregated data and develop a technique for developing network reachable queries for individually programmable devices to receive information produced by Logic Programs. This project incorporates reasoning modules over HTTP, raw data to predicate mapping modules, and data aggregation and input stream handling. Each section has its relevant overview and implementation documentation.

## RESTful HTTP Service, Smart Home Hub

A smart home environment may contain many devices with several different types of data formats and many events occurring on the network. A high level RESTful web service was created to handle event driven querying on the network and aggregate data in a central location. The data aggregation module is designed to process and handle storage of the several types of data formats on the network to transform into logical predicates and reason about in logic programs. The query building module allows for queries to be developed using logic programs to reason about aggregated information and distribute information over the network.

The service was developed in using cherrypy web framework, a simple pythonic wrapper over HTTP which allows for a lightweight implementation of the hub. This service relies heavily on RESTful techniques to include HTTP operations for sending and receiving data, and JSON representations of objects which many devices and other frameworks are equipped to handle.

This RESTful service is the entry point for all query definitions, query usage, data aggregation and central hub management. Below is the main class and associated configuration. Figure 2 outlines the main API endpoint definition for sending and receiving data on the network. The individual endpoints each have their own implementation definition and specified functionality in their respective sections.

        queryInfo.pop(&quot;mainLogic&quot;)

        return queryInfo

    @cherrypy.expose

    @cherrypy.popargs(&#39;queryName&#39;)

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_in()

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_out()

    def useQueryWithInput(self, queryName):

        queryInput = cherrypy.request.json

        queryInfo = self.queryHandler.getQueryInfo(queryName)

        if queryInfo is None:

            return {&quot;Result&quot; : &quot;Failure&quot;, &quot;Reason&quot; : &quot;Unable to fetch query info. Does this query exist?&quot;}

        solverOutput = self.clingoSolver.solveSkillWithInput(queryInfo, queryInput)

        return solverOutput

    @cherrypy.expose

    @cherrypy.popargs(&#39;queryName&#39;)

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_in()

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_out()

    def useQueryWithDatabase(self, queryName):

        queryInfo = self.queryHandler.getQueryInfo(queryName)

        if queryInfo is None:

            return {&quot;Result&quot;: &quot;Failure&quot;, &quot;Reason&quot;: &quot;Unable to fetch query info. Does this query exist?&quot;}

        solverOutput = self.clingoSolver.solveQueryWithDeviceDatabase(queryInfo)

        return {&quot;output&quot; : str(solverOutput)}

    @cherrypy.expose

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_out()

    def getQueryList(self):

        queryInfo = self.queryHandler.getAllQueries()

        return queryInfo

Each API endpoint functionality is appropriately defined by its name. The endpoints useQueryWithDatabase and useQueryWithInput define two different ways of accessing a query. A useQueryWithDatabase requires data mapping definitions and useQueryWithInput requires input definitions in the query definition file. Both of these are explained in later sections of this document. ## Handling Input Streams

Diverse amounts of devices on the network causes a lot of issues in designing a relational database. This framework utilizes MongoDB document store for a non-relational, NoSQL database equipped to store new data sets.These diverse devices are assumed capable of being individually programmable to send data on a time controlled basis over HTTP.

Take a household global monitoring bus which sends information on which devices are in use. This device will need to send data frequently to inform the central hub what is going on. It can be programmed to POST data records every 10 seconds to the HTTP endpoint at /addDeviceData/deviceTracker. This is defined below at this endpoint on the server side:

    @cherrypy.expose

    @cherrypy.popargs(&#39;deviceName&#39;)

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_in()

    @cherrypy.tools.json\_out()

    def addDeviceData(self, deviceName):

        print &quot;test&quot;

        deviceData = cherrypy.request.json

        print deviceData

        addDataResult = self.deviceHandler.addData(deviceName, deviceData)

        return addDataResult

The device handler then adds data to the associated collection which encapsulates data specific to that device. This is displayed below:

    def addData(self, deviceName, deviceData):

        print &quot;adding &quot; + str(deviceData) + &quot; to &quot; + deviceName

        self.deviceDb[deviceName].insert(deviceData)

        return {&quot;Result&quot; : &quot;Success&quot;}



As stated earlier, devices should be individually programmed for sending data based on time interval needs. Unfortunately individual devices are largely unable to integrate a standard format for programming for the time being, so this will not be a feature of this framework anytime soon.

## Query Building With Logic Modules

Overview

Query building involves defining the main logic file(the ASP program), an input(if any) an output, and device data mapping definitions. Building queries defines how devices on the network receive information from the central reasoning hub. Queries also define how collections of stored data are used in logic programs. The mapping of data to logic predicates is defined in a later section.

**Scenario**

Individual devices on the network may want to periodically check up to see if they are needed or not. A logic module can be built to handle decision making with many considerations to be made in the process of doing so. Here is an example program for a simple check to see if the air conditioner can remain on:

canTurnOff(&quot;AirConditioner&quot;) :- userNotHome, deviceOn(&quot;AirConditioner&quot;), decreasingTemp.

decreasingTemp :- temperature(Degrees, Time), temperature(Degrees1, Time1), Time &gt; Time1, Degrees &lt; Degrees1.

userNotHome :- movement(&quot;John&quot;, Time), movement(&quot;John&quot;, Time1), Time &gt; Time1, currentTime(CTime), CTime-Time &gt; 90.

currentTime(1180).

This program is simple, it states that if John has not moved in a while, he is not home. If the temperature records show that it is decreasing, then we generate knowledge for this fact. This corresponds to the following picture:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The question is how we can transform low level sensor data aggregated from input streams described above to low level predicates which we can use to reason about in our programs.

This is described in the query definition that will be sent to the central hub through an HTTP POST method. Queries are developed specifically for using certain devices and generating output for certain information consumers.

**Example Query**

Implementation

This module is accessed at two endpoints, one for creating a query and one for using a query. Additionally the central service allows for deletion of queries in case one needs to be redefined. The creation of the query works by storing the main logic as binary in the document store database along with all other definitions and descriptions relevant to the query.

The code for Query additions is shown below in Figure X. The input is validated for ensuring all relevant information is contained and the database is checked to see if the query already exists. Note that the Query class is just an encapsulation for easy transformation to JSON in a better formatted manner.



 def addQuery(self, queryInfo):

        queryName = queryInfo[&quot;queryName&quot;]

        try:

            self.queryValidator.validateInput(queryInfo)

        except ValidationError, e:

            return {&quot;Result&quot; : &quot;Failure&quot;, &quot;Reason&quot; : e.message}

        if self.queryCollection.find({&quot;queryName&quot; : queryName}).count() &gt; 0:

            return { &quot;Result &quot; : &quot;Failure&quot;, &quot;Reason&quot; : &quot;query Already Exists!&quot;}

        queryInfo[&quot;mainLogic&quot;] = str(queryInfo[&quot;mainLogic&quot;])

        newQuery = Query(queryInfo)

        queryId = self.queryCollection.insert\_one(newQuery.toJson()).inserted\_id

        return {&quot;Result&quot; : &quot;Success&quot;, &quot;SkillId&quot; : str(queryId)}

**Adding A Query**

The query triggering is event driven on request only if a device asks the service for results. If the query relies on database data, the predicates are generated prior to solving and grounded into the program. If the query has its own specific input data, predicates are grounded using the predicate class and clingo control object done similarly to the output processing defined below. Predicate generation implementation details are defined in the Data To Logic section of this document.

The solving is then done using the clingo python module. All relevant ground predicates are added and the most optimal(if exists) result is returned to the user. The clingo grounder/solver efficiently solves and then the output is processed as defined in the next paragraph. Below is the code for control solving the finished program:

    def solveControl(self, control):

        control.ground([(&quot;base&quot;, [])])

        solveFuture = control.solve\_async(self.\_on\_model, self.\_on\_finish)

        solveFuture.wait()

        modelJson = {&quot;predicates&quot; : []}

        #If unsat, list will be empty.

        if len(self.modelSymbols) == 0:

            return modelJson

        symbols = self.modelSymbols.pop()

        for symbol in range(0, len(symbols)):

            print symbols[symbol]

            predicateToAdd = Predicate(self.termDefinitions, symbols[symbol])

            modelJson[&quot;predicates&quot;].append( predicateToAdd.termJson )

        return modelJson

**Control Solving**

The output definition defines how symbols or predicate objects can be transformed for processing over the web. The service uses a class which can be instantiated with a clingo.Symbol object and a term or output definition which defines the variable ordering since clingo does not have a built in system for this. Figure X represents the python class which encapsulates these symbols and handles transformation between JSON and Symbols conversion

class Predicate:

    name = &quot;&quot;

    termJson = {}

    def \_\_init\_\_(self, termDefinitions=None, symbol=None):

        if termDefinitions != None and symbol != None:

            self.termJson = {}

            self.name = &quot;&quot;

            if symbol.type == SymbolType.Function:

                self.name = symbol.name

                self.termDefinition = termDefinitions[self.name]

                symArgs = symbol.arguments # Actual Values

                varNames = termDefinitions[self.name][&quot;variableNames&quot;] # Name Lookup

                if len(varNames) != len(symArgs):

                    raise Exception(&quot;Output definition did not match up with logic program output!&quot;)

                self.termJson.update({&quot;name&quot;: self.name})

                for ix in range(0, len(symArgs)):

                    if symArgs[ix].type == SymbolType.String:

                        self.termJson.update({varNames[ix] : symArgs[ix].string})

                    elif symArgs[ix].type == SymbolType.Number:

                        self.termJson.update({varNames[ix]: symArgs[ix].number})

                    else:

                        funcTerm = Predicate(termDefinitions, symArgs[ix])

                        self.termJson.update({varNames[ix] : funcTerm.termJson })

    def predicateFromJson(self, termDefinitions, symbolJson):

        self.termJson = symbolJson

        self.name = self.termJson[&#39;name&#39;]

    def fromInputJson(self, termDefinitions, predicateJson):

        self.name = predicateJson[&quot;predicateName&quot;]

        self.termJson = predicateJson

    def predicateFromBson(self, termDefinitions, symbolJson):

        self.termJson = json.loads(symbolJson)

        self.name = self.termJson[&#39;name&#39;]

    def toSymbol(self, modelProcessor):

        return modelProcessor.jsonToSymbol(self.termJson)

## Mapping Data To Logic

**Overview**

Figure X, a cutout of an above figure, shows low level sensor data transformation into logical predicates.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

This is an important component of the system and the mapping is performed during the query execution prior to logic program solving. Basically it will find all relevant data defined in the Query definition and transform it into logic predicates - extending the logic program signature to database data.

The input streams are basically a junk drawer of information and in order to sift through them we will define query specific data-to-logic mappings. In the future, work could be done to generalize this and incorporate machine learning techniques to learn from this data.

Take one of above device mapping definitions in the &quot;Needs AC&quot; query:

        {

            &quot;name&quot;: &quot;WeatherSensor&quot;,

            &quot;dataMappings&quot;: [

                {

                    &quot;mappingVariables&quot;: [

                        &quot;Degrees&quot;,

                        &quot;Time&quot;

                    ],

                    &quot;predicateName&quot;: &quot;temperature&quot;,

                    &quot;recordData&quot;: {

                        &quot;Degrees&quot;: &quot;temperatureRecorded&quot;,

                        &quot;Time&quot;: &quot;timeLogged&quot;

                    }

                }

            ]

        }

This definition states that there is a collection of data in our database named &quot;WeatherSensor&quot;, appropriately named to reflect its weather gauge functionality. Data mappings describes a predicate name which has two variables which are required in the mapping, Degrees and Time ordered respectively in the predicate. The predicateName key defines the name for the predicate. The recordData key is a mapping of each predicate variable to actual data that occurs in each record. In definitions, each variable requires a mapping to a values which are required to be in each record of a collection.

Below is a demonstration of this mapping:

## ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**Data transformation example**

**Implementation**

This mapping framework was implemented in python using pymongo for interfacing with the database. The code for mapping is below in Figure X. The deviceMappingDefinition parameter is taken from a query definition stored in the database. The mapping is done for each data record in a collection. Collections are expected to have single record types which have the required variables noted in the mapping definition.



    # This method maps data to predicates based on data mapping definition typically

    # defined in a query definition. For more information visit the documentation

    def mapCurrentDataToPredicates(self, deviceMappingDefinition):

        predicates = []

        for device in deviceMappingDefinition:

            deviceName = device[&quot;name&quot;]

            dataMappings = device[&quot;dataMappings&quot;]

            deviceDataCollection = self.deviceDb[deviceName]

            for mapping in dataMappings:

                predicateName = mapping[&quot;predicateName&quot;]

                mappingVariables = mapping[&quot;mappingVariables&quot;]

                mappedData = {}

                collectionCursor = deviceDataCollection.find({})

                #Iterate through all data records in a data specific collection

                for dataRecord in collectionCursor:

                    for variable in mappingVariables:

                        #Lookup in the definition which data key gives us our variable term

                        dataRecordKey = mapping[&quot;recordData&quot;][variable]

                        dataRecordValue = dataRecord[dataRecordKey]

                        #Convert BSON float data to int if needed

                        if type(dataRecordValue) == float:

                            dataRecordValue = int(dataRecordValue)

                        mappedData.update({ variable : dataRecordValue })

                    #Generate Predicate based on variable data mapping

                    predicate = {&quot;name&quot; : predicateName}

                    for variable in mappingVariables:

                        predicate.update({variable : mappedData[variable]})

                    predicates.append(self.\_convertPredicateToString(predicate, mappingVariables))

                    mappedData = {}

        return predicates

**Data mapping implementation algorithm.**

As defined in an above section, this mapping is ran each time a dependant query wants to revise previous knowledge by receiving the most updated data.

## Device Management With Clingo

Device management is one of the main demonstrations and components of this framework. The design of the device management module is in three sub-components - device use scheduling, profiling the user&#39;s habits and lastly the household makeup or what devices are present on the network. Currently this is defined manually but could later be extended to incorporate automated plug and play detection. The household makeup is defined as follows:

room(&quot;LivingRoom&quot;).

room(&quot;Kitchen&quot;).

room(&quot;DiningRoom&quot;).

room(&quot;Bathroom&quot;).

room(&quot;Bedroom&quot;).

lights(Room) :- room(Room).

appliance(&quot;Dishwasher&quot;).

appliance(&quot;WashingMachine&quot;).

appliance(&quot;Dryer&quot;).

appliance(&quot;Oven&quot;).

appliance(&quot;Stove&quot;).

appliance(&quot;Shutters&quot;).

device(DeviceName) :- lights(DeviceName).

device(DeviceName) :- appliance(DeviceName).

{deviceCost(DeviceName,Start,End,5\*(End-Start)) : appliance(DeviceName)} :- deviceOn(DeviceName,Start,End).

{deviceCost(DeviceName,Start,End,End-Start) : lights(DeviceName)} :- deviceOn(DeviceName,Start,End).

#show deviceCost/4.

The main scheduling module is a logic program which in itself generates time slots and states to minimize cost with one additional constraint that if a user requires the device, it must be on.  Below is the code for the main scheduling module.

minutes(0..1440).

timeslot(Start, End) :- minutes(Start), minutes(End), Start &lt; End, Start\5 = 0, End\5 = 0.

{deviceOn(DeviceName,Start,End) } :- device(DeviceName), timeslot(Start,End).

% Devices must be on when needed.

:- not deviceOn(DeviceName,Start,End), needDevice(DeviceName,Start,End).

% All Device scheduling needs an associated cost.

:- deviceOn(DeviceName,Start,End), not deviceCost(DeviceName,Start,End,\_).

#minimize { Cost : deviceCost(DeviceName, Start, End, Cost)}.

#show deviceOn/3.

#show device/1.

This allows for elaboration tolerance as the needDevice predicate can be defined in a user profiling module. Many other cases may generate this knowledge so we can decide it separately in another module, the userRequirements module defined below:

% Rooms are devices as they need to be &#39;turned on&#39; when used - in this case the lights.

needDevice(RoomName,Start,End) :- userUses(RoomName,Start,End).

% Entry Lights should be scheduled to turn on 5 minutes before a user comes home

% Assumes living room is the entry room

needDevice(&quot;LivingRoom&quot;,Time-5,Time+20) :- userWillBeHome(Time).

% Schedule the user to use the oven at least once per day

1{ needDevice(&quot;Oven&quot;,1080..1200,1110..1230) }1.

% Schedule the user to use the laundry if he has not done it this week

1{ needDevice(&quot;WashingMachine&quot;,1080..1200,1140..1260) }1 :- not doneLaundry.

needDevice(&quot;Dryer&quot;,Start+30,Start+30+45) :- needDevice(&quot;WashingMachine&quot;,Start,\_).

{not doneLaundry}.

% Turn off all lights if the user is sleeping

:- userSleeps(SleepStart,SleepEnd), deviceOn(&quot;Bedroom&quot;,LightsStart,LightsEnd), LightsEnd &gt; SleepStart.

As seen in the program, needDevice is defined in several points where this knowledge could be generated. The userSleeps predicate is an observation which defines that bedroom lights must be off when the user is sleeping. Additionally we want the lights to be on just prior to a user coming home, since nobody wants to come home to a dark home. The userWillBeHome predicate is located in a developing module which is designed to profile the user. This is displayed below:

# User Profiling and Monitoring with LPMLN

The project currently is lacking in this but the development branch in progress is to add LPMLN to profile the user and make most likely determinations about high level events. Currently the central service is equipped to only return raw text output and cannot process LPMLN modules or perform control solving with the same ease as there is no python API for LPMLN programs.

Here are some example LPMLN Programs the project has implemented and will be expanding on.

**Condition Monitoring**

1 fellAsleep(Person) :- lieDown(Person).

1 fellAsleep(Person) :- tookMedication(Person).

1 fellAsleep(Person) :- normalHeartRate(Person).

1 fellAsleep(Person) :- inadequateSleep(Person).

1 fainted(Person) :- lieDown(Person).

1 fainted(Person) :- not tookMedication(Person).

1 fainted(Person) :- highHeartRate(Person).

1 fainted(Person) :- lowBloodSugar(Person)

1 fainted(Person) :- not tookMedication(Person).

% Generate no answer sets for which a person has fainted but is still

% conscious and well.

:- fellAsleep(Person), not lieDown(Person).

:- fainted(Person), not lieDown(Person).

% Person cannot faint(emergency) and fall asleep(non-emergency)

:- fellAsleep(Person), fainted(Person).

% Calorie counts

calorieCount(Day,Count) :- mealsForDay(Day,1,MealName1), mealsForDay(Day,2,MealName2), mealsForDay(Day,3,MealName3),

    meal(MealName1,\_,Cal1,\_,\_,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,Cal2,\_,\_,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,Cal3,\_,\_,\_),

    Count = @sum( Cal1, Cal2, Cal3 ).

fatCount(Day,Count) :- mealsForDay(Day,1,MealName1), mealsForDay(Day,2,MealName2), mealsForDay(Day,3,MealName3),

    meal(MealName1,\_,\_,Fat1,\_,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,\_,Fat2,\_,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,\_,Fat3,\_,\_),

    Count = @sum( Fat1, Fat2, Fat3 ).

carbCount(Day,Count) :- mealsForDay(Day,1,MealName1), mealsForDay(Day,2,MealName2), mealsForDay(Day,3,MealName3),

    meal(MealName1,\_,\_,\_,Carb1,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,\_,\_,Carb2,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,\_,\_,Carb3,\_),

    Count = @sum( Carb1, Carb2, Carb3 ).

proteinCount(Day,Count) :- mealsForDay(Day,1,MealName1), mealsForDay(Day,2,MealName2), mealsForDay(Day,3,MealName3),

    meal(MealName1,\_,Prot1,\_,\_,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,Prot2,\_,\_,\_), meal(MealName1,\_,Prot3,\_,\_,\_),

    Count = @sum( Prot1, Prot2, Prot3 ).

% User preferences for optimization

preference(highProtein).
